## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of security in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Security is the bounded protection structure
through which identity verification,
boundary preservation,
access protection,
masking,
and integrity assurance
become meaningful.

Security is not merely denial.
It is the active maintenance of trusted boundaries
without destroying operational usability.

## architectural_position
Security sits between:
- identity and permission
- runtime execution
- policy enforcement
- governance oversight
- audit and observability

## required_behavior
- trust boundary must remain explicit
- verification basis must remain explicit
- current and historical security states must remain distinguishable
- masking and integrity behavior must remain explicit

## canonical_rules
- security state must not silently widen privilege
- masking must remain identifiable as masking
- integrity failures must remain attributable
- historical security trace must remain queryable
- ambiguous security scope fails closed

## state_model
The security domain distinguishes:
- normal protected state
- restricted state
- challenged state
- escalated security state
- historical security state

## actor_boundary
- subject
- verifier
- operator
- reviewer
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if trust boundary is unclear, fail closed
- if verification basis is missing, deny sensitive path
- if integrity is uncertain, escalate or restrict
- if state becomes historical, preserve trace

## review_checklist
- trust boundary is explicit
- verification basis is explicit
- masking/integrity behavior is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
